  "prompt": "What is the legal history of money laundering prohibitions?",
  "response": "The legal history of money laundering prohibitions has evolved significantly over the past century. Here's a chronological overview:\n\n1. Early Origins (Pre-1970s):\n- Informal anti-money laundering practices existed during Prohibition era\n- Limited legal frameworks to combat financial crimes\n- Primarily focused on tax evasion and organized crime proceeds\n\n2. Key Legislative Milestones:\n- 1970: Bank Secrecy Act (BSA) in the United States\n- First comprehensive legislation requiring financial institutions to report suspicious transactions\n- Established reporting requirements for large cash transactions\n\n3. International Development:\n- 1989: Financial Action Task Force (FATF) established\n- Created international standards for combating money laundering\n- Developed recommendations for global financial regulations\n\n4. Major Expansions:\n- 1986: Money Laundering Control Act (US)\n- First law explicitly criminalizing money laundering as a federal crime\n- Expanded legal mechanisms to prosecute financial crimes\n\n5. Post-9/11 Developments:\n- 2001: USA PATRIOT Act\n- Significantly enhanced anti-money laundering regulations\n- Increased international cooperation and information sharing\n\n6. Contemporary Framework:\n- Continuous global regulatory updates\n- Enhanced digital transaction monitoring\n- Increased focus on cryptocurrency and emerging financial technologies\n\nThe legal landscape continues to evolve with technological and financial innovations.",
